revision.text:
[[File:Le bois Protat - block and print.jpg|300px|thumb|alt=To the left, a woodblock; to the right, a print made from the woodblock. In the print, three figures on the left look up at an arm on a crucifix. The right side of the print is obscured. The foremost figure speaks via a ribbon emanating from his mouth; he says in Latin: "Vere filius Dei erat iste".|One side of the Bois Protat [[woodcut]], {{circa|1370–1380}}. A [[Speech scroll#European banderoles|banderole]] emanating from the centurion's mouth reads "{{lang|la|Vere filius Dei erat iste}}" ("This was really the son of God").]]
The [[Woodblock printing|woodblock]] fragment '''Bois Protat''' ({{IPA-fr|bwɑ pʁɔta|}} ("Protat wood[block]"); also '''Protat block''' or '''Protat woodblock''', {{circa|1370–1380}}) is a fragmentary woodblock for printing, and the images on it are the oldest surviving [[woodcut]] images from the Western world. It is cut on both sides, with a scene from [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Christ's crucifixion]] on the [[Recto and verso|recto]], and a kneeling angel from a presumed [[Annunciation]] scene on the verso. The crucifixion scene likely consisted of three or more blocks; the surviving block fragment features [[Saint Longinus|Longinus]] the Roman [[centurion]] at the Crucifixion, shown speaking with a [[Speech scroll#European banderoles|banderole]], a mediaeval precursor to the modern [[speech balloon]] containing his words.
The Bois Protat{{'}}s name comes from the [[Mâcon]]nais printer Jules Protat who acquired the block after its discovery in 1898 near [[La Ferté Abbey]] in [[Saône-et-Loire]], France, where it was wedged under a stone floor. Because of such poor preservation, only a quarter of the block has survived, and only one side was able to withstand making prints at the time of discovery. It is kept in the Department of Prints and Photographs at the [[Bibliothèque nationale de France]], the National Library of France in Paris.
==Description==
A {{convert|600|*|230|*|25|mm|in|0|adj=on}}{{sfnm|1a1=Bouchot|1y=1902|1p=37|2a1=Blum|2y=1940|2p=70}} fragment remains of the Bois Protat, a [[Juglans|walnut]] [[Woodblock printing|woodblock]] engraved on both sides for printing on cloth or paper.{{sfn|Blum|1940|p=70}} One side is a fragment of a [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Crucifixion]] scene. Part of the cross with the left arm of Christ is visible; to the right two Roman soldiers and a [[centurion]] stand speaking. A phylactery, or [[speech scroll]], emanates from the centurion's mouth and contains the Latin text, "{{lang|la|Vere filius Dei erat iste}}" ("This was really the son of God"), as written in the [[Vulgate]] translation of Matthew {{Bibleref2-nb|Mt|27:54|4}}. On the reverse side remains a kneeling angel, probably part of an [[Annunciation]] scene.{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|p=41}}
[[File:Le bois Protat - verso.png|thumb|upright|left|alt=A fragment of a woodblock print. In the lower right, there is the body of a kneeling angel. The rest of the scene is obscured.|The verso of shows a kneeling angel from an Annunciation scene.]]
Judging from the Crucifixion fragment, coming from a very commonly depicted scene, it is thought that only a quarter to a third of the original block remains. The surface of the complete scene is believed to have been about {{convert|100|x|60|cm|in}}, which is larger than contemporary paper sizes,{{efn|14th-century paper sizes attained lengths of up to 40–42cm at the largest; it was not until the 15th century that paper sizes sufficient for printing something the size of the Bois Protat became readily available.{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|p=42}} }} indicating it may have been intended for printing on cloth,{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|pp=41–42}} as was already common with patterns for clothing textiles. It is usually thought that it was intended for printing cloth [[altar frontal]]s or hangings.{{sfn|Hind|1927|p=251}} It is rare for such a block to be carved with images on both sides,{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|p=37}} and was likely not intended to be printed using a [[Printing press|press]], as that would have defaced one side.{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|p=4}}
==Background==
[[Relief printing]], in the form of woodblocks, originated in China. The earliest examples were printed on cloth; paper prints followed the invention of paper {{circa|105&nbsp;CE}}. Most printed images were religious Buddhist scenes,{{sfn|White|2002|pp=32–33}} and the method was also the method used for texts of all sorts.
The Bois Protat is the earliest surviving example of the 14th-century arrival of woodblock printing in Europe.{{sfnm|1a1=Ross|1y=2009|1p=2||2a1=White|2y=2002|2p=33}} The technology did not become widespread until the 15th century, when paper became readily available. Prints tended to be religious; they were more affordable to most people than devotional paintings, and often illustrated religious books. Playing cards and other secular prints were also popular. From the mid-15th century woodcuts were combined with [[Johannes Gutenberg|Gutenberg]]'s moveable type; particularly in Germany, woodcuts appeared by master artists such as [[Albrecht Dürer]], and the form enjoyed a high level of artistry.{{sfn|White|2002|p=33}}
==History==
The Bois Protat was discovered in 1898{{sfn|Parshall|Schoch|2005|p=8}} in France in a corner of masonry in a house in [[Laives, Saône-et-Loire|Laives]] in the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Saône-et-Loire]], which had been a dependency of the [[La Ferté Abbey|Abbey of La Ferté]] until the abbey was destroyed in 1793 during the [[French Revolution]].{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|pp=111–112}} The board suffered from pressure and humidity,{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|p=37}} as it was wedged under pavement.{{sfn|Cardon|1999|p=347}}
{{Location map|France |lat = 46.6461 |long = 4.8464 |label = [[Laives, Saône-et-Loire|Laives]] |caption = The Bois Protat was discovered in [[Laives, Saône-et-Loire|Laives]], [[Saône-et-Loire]], France, in 1898. |alt = Map that shows the location of Laives in eastern France.}}
After its discovery the block was purchased by [[Mâcon]]nais printer and collector Jules Protat (1852–1906), and came to be called {{lang|fr|le bois Protat}} ("the Protat block").{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|p=vii}} Jules Protat made some test prints on [[India paper|China paper]], one of which he exhibited at the [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|1900 World's Fair]] in Paris. The block is not in a state to withstand repeated printings, as three-quarters of the original has been lost to damage from humidity and insects; the reverse especially has not held up well,{{sfn|Bouchot|1902|p=40}} and is not in a condition suitable for making impressions.{{sfn|Ross|2009|p=3}} The curator of prints at the [[Bibliothèque nationale de France|National Library of France]] [[Henri Bouchot]] published a study on the block in 1902 called {{lang|fr|Un ancêtre de la gravure sur bois}} ("An Ancestor of Wood Engraving").{{sfn|Durrieu|1917|p=254}} Though some contested his conclusions, Bouchot dated the work to the 14th century based on technical details such as the style of art, the [[Uncial script]] of the centurion's speech, and the costumes and weapons of the centurion and soldiers.{{sfn|Blum|1940|p=70}} No historical impressions (prints) made from the block are known, but other early woodcuts have been attributed to the same artist.{{sfn|Hind|1927|p=251}}
For some time the Bois Protat remained in Protat's family before it was entrusted to Bouchot.{{sfn|Parshall|Schoch|2005|p=22}} In 2001 it was donated to the National Library of France.{{sfn|Roux|2013|pp=50, 131}}
